PEP 508 ENVIRONMENT MARKERS IN UV
===================================
How markers like `requests; python_version > "3.8"` are parsed and evaluated.

---

1. MARKER PARSING CODE — CRATE AND MODULE
------------------------------------------

Dedicated crate: `uv-pep508`
  Handles the full PEP 508 dependency specifier grammar, including markers.

Key files:

  crates/uv-pep508/src/marker/mod.rs (lines 1-50)
    Module root; exports MarkerTree, MarkerExpression, MarkerOperator, MarkerEnvironment.

  crates/uv-pep508/src/marker/parse.rs (lines 1-700+)
    - `parse_marker_operator()` (lines 20-69): lexes `==`, `!=`, `<`, `>`, `in`, `not in`, etc.
    - `parse_marker_value()` (lines 75-154): lexes quoted strings and variable names
    - Full PEP 508 expression grammar with validated comparisons; emits warnings for
      invalid operations (e.g., a non-`==`/`!=` operator applied to `extra`).

  crates/uv-pep508/src/marker/tree.rs
    - `MarkerTree` enum — the compiled, interned representation of a marker expression.
    - `evaluate()` / `evaluate_reporter_impl()` — evaluation logic.

  crates/uv-pep508/src/marker/environment.rs (lines 12-30)
    - `MarkerEnvironment` struct — holds concrete values for all PEP 508 marker variables:
        python_version, python_full_version, implementation_version,
        implementation_name, os_name, sys_platform, platform_system,
        platform_release, platform_version, platform_machine,
        platform_python_implementation.

Markers enter the system when requirements are parsed:
  crates/uv-pep508/src/lib.rs (lines 124-142)
  `Requirement::from_str()` — the `marker` field of the resulting `Requirement` struct
  holds the parsed `MarkerTree`.


2. WHEN ARE MARKERS EVALUATED?
-------------------------------

Markers are evaluated at RESOLUTION TIME (not parse time; not install time for lock
file generation).

Evidence — resolution-time filtering:
  crates/uv-resolver/src/manifest.rs (lines 138-149)

    .filter(move |requirement| {
        requirement.evaluate_markers(env.marker_environment(), lookahead.extras())
    })

  Requirements whose markers evaluate to false are filtered out before the resolver ever
  sees them. This is the primary gate.

Lock-file installation phase:
  Markers are re-evaluated when building the installation graph from the lock file
  (crates/uv-resolver/src/lock/installable.rs). Packages already in the lock file are
  not re-resolved, but their markers are checked to decide whether to install them in the
  current environment.

In summary:
  - Parse time  : MarkerTree is built (syntax only, no environment values yet)
  - Resolution  : Markers evaluated against target MarkerEnvironment — main gating point
  - Install time: Markers re-evaluated against the actual runtime environment


3. WHERE MARKERS GATE PACKAGE INCLUSION IN THE LOCK FILE
---------------------------------------------------------

File: crates/uv-resolver/src/lock/installable.rs

Three distinct gates, all using the same pattern — evaluate returns false → continue
(skip adding the dependency edge):

Path 1 — dev/optional dependencies (lines 159-170):

    if !dep.complexified_marker.evaluate(
        marker_env,
        activated_projects.iter().copied(),
        activated_extras.iter().chain(additional_activated_extras.iter()).copied(),
        activated_groups.iter().copied(),
    ) {
        continue;
    }

Path 2 — production dependencies (lines 480-487):

    if !dep.complexified_marker.evaluate(
        marker_env,
        activated_projects.iter().copied(),
        activated_extras.iter().copied(),
        activated_groups.iter().copied(),
    ) {
        continue;
    }

Path 3 — root-level requirements (lines 231-233):

    if !dependency.marker.evaluate(marker_env, &[]) {
        continue;
    }

When the marker evaluates to false, `continue` causes the loop to skip adding the
dependency node/edge to the graph, so the package is absent from the install set for
that environment.


4. CONCRETE CODE PATH: DEPENDENCY SKIPPED BY MARKER
-----------------------------------------------------

Example requirement: `numpy; python_version >= "3.9"`

Step 1 — Parse time (uv-pep508/src/lib.rs:124)
  `Requirement::from_str("numpy; python_version >= \"3.9\"")` produces:
    Requirement { name: "numpy", marker: MarkerTree(<python_version >= 3.9>), ... }

Step 2 — Manifest filtering at resolution time (uv-resolver/src/manifest.rs:140)
  For a Python 3.8 resolver environment:

    requirement.evaluate_markers(env_3_8, [])
    // evaluates: 3.8 >= 3.9 → false
    // .filter() drops this requirement; numpy never enters the resolver

  For a Python 3.9 resolver environment:

    requirement.evaluate_markers(env_3_9, [])
    // evaluates: 3.9 >= 3.9 → true
    // requirement passes through; numpy is resolved from PyPI

Step 3 — evaluate() implementation (uv-pep508/src/marker/tree.rs:990-1111)

    pub fn evaluate(self, env: &MarkerEnvironment, extras: &[ExtraName]) -> bool {
        self.evaluate_reporter_impl(env, ExtrasEnvironment::from_extras(extras), &mut TracingReporter)
    }

    fn evaluate_reporter_impl(self, env, extras, reporter) -> bool {
        match self.kind() {
            MarkerTreeKind::True  => return true,
            MarkerTreeKind::False => return false,
            MarkerTreeKind::Version(marker) => {
                for (range, tree) in marker.edges() {
                    if range.contains(env.get_version(marker.key())) {
                        return tree.evaluate_reporter_impl(env, extras, reporter);
                    }
                }
            }
            MarkerTreeKind::String(marker) => {
                for (range, tree) in marker.children() {
                    if range.contains(env.get_string(marker.key())) {
                        return tree.evaluate_reporter_impl(env, extras, reporter);
                    }
                }
            }
            // ...
        }
        false  // no matching range → false
    }

Step 4 — Lock file graph building (uv-resolver/src/lock/installable.rs:479-487)
  When building the install graph from the lock file for a Python 3.8 target:

    for dep in deps {
        if !dep.complexified_marker.evaluate(marker_env, ...) {
            continue;  // numpy skipped — not added to the install graph
        }
        let dep_dist = self.lock().find_by_id(&dep.package_id);
        // ... add node and edge  ← only reached for deps whose markers pass
    }


SUMMARY
-------

Stage          | What happens to markers
---------------|---------------------------------------------------
Parse time     | Built into MarkerTree (interned, efficient data structure); no evaluation
Resolution     | Evaluated against target MarkerEnvironment in manifest.rs filter — primary gate
Lock file      | Markers stored alongside each dependency entry
Install time   | Re-evaluated in installable.rs; false → continue (dependency not installed)

Supported marker variables (MarkerEnvironment, environment.rs:12-30):
  python_version, python_full_version, implementation_version, implementation_name,
  os_name, sys_platform, platform_system, platform_release, platform_version,
  platform_machine, platform_python_implementation

Supported operators (MarkerOperator):
  Version: ==  !=  <  <=  >  >=  ~=  ===
  String:  in  not in
  Extras:  ==  !=  (only == and != are valid per PEP 508)

